nt of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lyne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot, Niall.","English: variant of   Line   1.","Irish: from <b>Ó Laighin</b>, a variant of   Lane   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Line","meanings":["English: from the medieval female personal name <i>Line</i>, a shortened form of <i>Cateline</i> (see   Catlin  ) and of various other names such as <i>Emmeline</i> and <i>Adeline</i>, containing the Anglo-Norman French diminutive suffix <i>-line</i> (originally a double diminutive, composed of the elements <i>-el</i> and <i>-in</i>).","Americanized form of German   Lein  .","In some cases possibly also French (<b>Liné</b>): metonymic occupational name for a linen weaver or a linen merchant, from an Old French adjective <i>liné</i> ‘made of linen’."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert De Lyne was born in 1190, in Midlothian, Scotland, his father, David de Lyne, was 41 and his mother, De Lyne, was 38. He married de Lyne in 1218, in Peeblesshire, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"1190–":"1190–Surnud","1165–Male":"1165–Surnud","1190–Male":"1190–Surnud","1193–Female":"1193–Surnud","1218–Male":"1218–Surnud","1220–Male":"1220–Surnud","1149–Male":"1149–Surnud","1152–Female":"1152–Surnud","1190":"1190","1149":"1149","about 1218":"umbes 1218","1220":"1220","1165":"1165","1152":"1152","1193":"1193","1218":"1218","Peeblesshire, Scotland":"Peeblesshire, Scotland","Dalry, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Dalry, Ayrshire, Scotland","Midlothian, Scotland":"Midlothian, Scotland"},"fi":{"1190–":"1190–Kuollut","1165–Male":"1165–Kuollut","1190–Male":"1190–Kuollut","1193–Female":"1193–Kuollut","1218–Male":"1218–Kuollut","1220–Male":"1220–Kuollut","1149–Male":"1149–Kuollut","1152–Female":"1152–Kuollut","1190":"1190","1149":"1149","about 1218":"noin 1218","1220":"1220","1165":"1165","1152":"1152","1193":"1193","1218":"1218","Peeblesshire, Scotland":"Peeblesshire, Scotland","Dalry, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Dalry, Ayrshire, Scotland","Midlothian, Scotland":"Midlothian, Scotland"},"fr":{"1190–":"1190–Décédé","1165–Male":"1165–Décédé","1190–Male":"1190–Décédé","1193–Female":"1193–Décédée","1218–Male":"1218–Décédé","1220–Male":"1220–Décédé","1149–Male":"1149–Décédé","1152–Female":"1152–Décédée","1190":"1190","1149":"1149","about 1218":"environ 1218","1220":"1220","1165":"1165","1152":"1152","1193":"1193","1218":"1218","Peeblesshire, Scotland":"Valle de Twede, Écosse","Dalry, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Dalry, Ayrshire, Écosse","Midlothian, Scotland":"Midlothian, Écosse","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Robert De Lyne est né en 1190, à Midlothian, Écosse, son père, David de Lyne, avait 41 ans et sa mère, De Lyne, avait 38 ans. Il a épousé de Lyne en 1218, à Valle de Twede,